                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3x63br6g/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>well being of the whole body. Some expressed fears<lb/> that the union once formed\n                would if under the guidance<lb/> of faithless shepherds work much mischief. You<lb/>\n                are aware in what light innovations are held by many<lb/> and the passage in<lb/>\n                <persName>Dr. Wise's</persName> address “if we do not<lb/> stimulate all the\n                congregations to establish good schools<lb/> and to institute a reform in their\n                synagogues <hi rend=\"underline\">on</hi><lb/>\n                <hi rend=\"underline\">modern Jewish principles</hi> &amp;c &amp;c” was much\n                ani<lb/>=madverted upon, and I cannot help wishing the revd<lb/> gentleman had not\n                put it forth, though I am persuaded he<lb/> meant not that any thing should be\n                attempted contrary<lb/> to received Laws and customs; but the word “Reform” has<lb/>\n                acquired somehow or another a portentous meaning to<lb/> ears that revere, and\n                properly revere our ancient institu<lb/>=tions. In short so many and conflicting\n                were the sentiments<lb/> and opinions expressed at the meeting of the\n                congregation<lb/> and at that of the committee, as decided me on acceding<lb/> to\n                    <persName>Mr. Alexander Kursheedt's</persName>, and other friends' with, as<lb/>\n                well as on responding to your general invitation to give<lb/> through the\n                    <sic>occident</sic> some of my ideas upon the subject<lb/> I send you “Letters.\n                on the formation of a Union of<lb/> the congregations of Israelites in the\n                    <placeName>United States</placeName>” and<lb/> will as quickly as possible\n                follow it up with others so<lb/> that by the time the meeting takes place the public\n                will<lb/> be in possession of my views “which will be taken only<lb/> for as much as\n                they may be worth” If you deem it<lb/> necessary I will thank you to announce in the\n                    <sic>occident</sic><lb/> that I perfectly coincide in the propriety of holding a\n                meeting<lb/> and will attend it if possible. Might it not be as well<lb/> to make\n                the period a little later, say <date>Rosh Hodesh<lb/> Sivan</date>, corresponding to\n                the <date>22<hi rend=\"sup\">nd</hi> May</date>, as by that time<lb/> travelling\n                especially from the <placeName>west</placeName> may be expected to<lb/> be attended\n                with less fatigue, inconvenience and perhaps<lb/> less danger: <placeName>New\n                    York</placeName> I think should be the place</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3x63br6g/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
